TextChange: Hello there  => What produces a more successful employee, competition, or cooperation? I think both are valid options, are probably depending on the person, one may be more suitable then the other. However, the natural order of how species strive, thrive, and survive is through competition. The person or animal who is the smartest, strongest, or most clever is the one that will in the end survive and advance. And if you are not one of those things, you better work to get better, so you aren’t the one left behind. \nI think the simplest form of this comes through in sports. If I’m a basketball player and I want to get better, I have two options. To play lower competition than me, so I can exploit my strengths and avoid my weaknesses, or play better competition than me, so the opponent and exploit my weaknesses and avoid my strengths. Now in which one of those scenarios am I ultimately getting better? The one where my weaknesses are exposed, and I’m forced to improve on \n
